[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Under domain-driven design, the structure and language of software code (class names, class methods, class variables) should match the business domain.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] For example: if software processes loan applications, it might have classes like "loan application", "customers", and methods such as "accept offer" and "withdraw".
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Critics of domain-driven design argue that developers must typically implement a great deal of isolation and encapsulation to maintain the model as a pure and helpful construct.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] While domain-driven design provides benefits such as maintainability, Microsoft recommends it only for complex domains where the model provides clear benefits in formulating a common understanding of the domain.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] The term was coined by Eric Evans in his book of the same name published in 2003.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Domain-driven design articulates a number of high-level concepts and practices.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Of primary importance is a *domain* of the software, the subject area to which the user applies a program.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Software's developers build a *domain model*: a system of abstractions that describes selected aspects of a domain and can be used to solve problems related to that domain.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] These aspects of domain-driven design aim to foster a *common language* shared by domain experts, users, and developers—the *ubiquitous language*.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] The ubiquitous language is used in the domain model and for describing system requirements.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Ubiquitous language is one of the pillars of DDD together with *strategic design* and *tactical design*.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] In domain-driven design, the domain layer is one of the common layers in an object-oriented multilayered architecture.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Domain-driven design recognizes multiple kinds of models.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] For example, an *entity* is an object defined not by its attributes, but its identity.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] As an example, most airlines assign a unique number to seats on every flight: this is the seat's identity.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] In contrast, a *value object* is an immutable object that contains attributes but has no conceptual identity.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] When people exchange business cards, for instance, they only care about the information on the card (its attributes) rather than trying to distinguish between each unique card.
